4:
Here's the book, Jay.
...I trust you've got the goods.
6:
Of course! With a fake dust jacket over 
the cover and everything. Take a peek 
inside.
9:
Let's see... *flip*
Ah, yes! The forbidden scripture, 
penned by men of yore—Bonkers 
Honkers!
16:
You're always in such a hurry, boy! 
Pay your elders some respect, hm?
19:
Jay's right! We've been around long 
enough to refine our tastes. You'll find 
no better than Bonkers Honkers, 
sonny! Come have a peek.
22:
If you say "Bonkers Honkers" one more 
time, I'm gonna lose it.
25:
Hmph, Bonkers Honkers is a work of 
art, the prize gem of our generation! 
Why, I still remember the day forty 
years ago when I found a copy on 
a shipwrecked—
36:
Ugh, I can't believe you dragged me 
out here to listen to two wrinkled 
geezers drool over "honkers."
39:
Hah! Don't be such a grump—it was 
a necessary evil to get my paws on 
THIS.
45:
All right, calm down. It's a book on 
human anatomy, yes—but of the 
anthropological variety. Nothing 
untowards.
53:
Hmm, to put it simply, it's an 
academic text exploring human and 
beastfolk's biological origins.
54:
You see, humans and beastfolk may 
not be so different as we thought.
57:
This book explores the hypothesis that 
humans are indeed a variety of 
beastfolk—monkeyfolk—and illustrates 
evolutionary similarities between 
humans and primates.
65:
Show a little more interest, boy! Aren't 
you curious? About humans? About 
us?
68:
...Not really? What difference would it 
make if I knew? It wouldn't change 
who I am.
71:
Just as learning your lineage didn't 
inspire you to reclaim your throne? 
King Selenius Whitetail.
75:
What, would you rather put ME in 
charge? Claw's clearly a better fit—I'd 
just be in the way.
78:
To be entirely honest, Claudius IS 
a better fit, but...
81:
No, I'll leave it there. I'm a curious man, 
always hungry for new knowledge. 
That's why they call me a sage!
84:
Do people REALLY call you a sage, or 
did you just make it up yourself, old 
fart?
88:
Of course I'm a real sage! My curiosity 
was so insatiable, the catfolk kicked 
me out of village—ask anyone old 
enough to remember!
96:
Well, suit yourself. No one's gonna kick 
you outta Starview for reading about 
monkeys.
101:
I wonder... was it chance or fate that 
led me to them?
105:
Either way, I'm with those kids now, 
and I'll not let this opportunity escape 
me.
110:
Hmm, now THAT'S interesting. I see, 
that would mean... No, what if it's—
hmm...
113:
To think I can walk straight into the 
Oracles' Hall... Times sure have 
changed. The godkings used to have 
this place  sealed off to anyone but 
themselves.
115:
It MUST be related to their divine 
wisdom. The Whitetails brought 
prosperity to the catfolk for 
generations with that knowledge.
117:
The Whitetails were strong and wise, 
yes, but I don't believe they were 
divinity themselves.
119:
Perhaps the ancient kings' knowledge 
came from other worlds—perceived by 
the common folk as heavenly realms 
amidst the Stars? But that's only one 
theory—
132:
Good golly, girl, you gave me a scare! 
What do you need?
135:
Alk said dinner is almost ready. I came 
to inform you.
138:
Is it already that late? I'll be there in 
a bit, I've still got things to check 
before Claudius catches me.
146:
Oh, all right, don't give me the kitten 
eyes, grampa's coming. I can sneak 
back in later.
150:
Stella, child, tell me. Do you ever want 
to learn more about yourself and the 
worlds out there?
162: I am also very curious about you.
168:
I used to be alone. Then I met Alk, 
followed by Light and many others.
169:
I learn new things every time I meet 
someone, so I would like to know more 
about them.
172:
Marina taught me to search for 
treasures. I think for me, those 
treasures are all of you.
176:
Oh, to be young! That sounds like the 
perfect goal for a bright-eyed bushy-
tailed kid like you.
180:
Enough chat. Wouldn't want YOUR 
dinner to go cold because of me. Let's 
hurry on back to Alk.
189:
*sigh* I let myself get too caught up in 
the past. Always have.
192:
Almost said something sentimental 
there. *shake* All right, Jay, back on 
track!
